2016:
• Comcast has been experiencing pain points around marketing data mapping for some time.
• Comcast is building a $1.5 billion Innovation and Technology Center next to the company headquarters in Philadelphia, expected to open in 2018.
• Comcast has recently contracted EdgeConnex for data center hosting on the East Coast.
• Comcast's current IT focus is the Resiliency Program, a long-term ongoing project intended to improve incident management and response processes, as well as infrastructure reliability and core platform efficiency.  This program currently covers 30+ applications as well.


Comcast Corporation's IT staff exists in numerous locations all across the country. Top IT executives are based out of company's headquarters in Philadelphia, PA.  The Chief Information Officer (CIO) oversees all stages of the technology initiatives, and strategic road mapping to align IT planning with current business needs. The IT department is also known as Comcast Enterprise Technology (CET).

Following the company's purchase of NBCUniversal in 2010 and 2011, relatively little change was made to NBCUniversal's internal structure. Some Comcast business units are now under NBC Universal's wing. NBCUniversal is maintained in a separate profile in RainKing.

Vice presidents and senior directors are in charge of the Eastern Division, the Central Division, the North Central Division, and the Western Division, the latter of which includes Comcast California. The company's Chief Technology Officer works to coordinate external technology programs with corresponding requirements for the internal department.

Customer Care operations are a primary concern for the telecommunications company, and a new call center was built in 2011.

Comcast Converged Products houses an IT staff led by the Vice President. This executive handles technical operations and architecture operations.

A vast IT staff at Comcast corporate supports the internal corporate infrastructure. Several of the company's vice presidents govern IT functions such as corporate systems, project management, IT architecture, and risk management and security. Other directors and managers direct more specific IT areas like the company's data centers, Internet Systems Engineering, application availability, software development, and anti-abuse technology.

The company maintains numerous data centers throughout the country and is concentrating heavily on cloud computing (internal private cloud) and virtualization. That goal will be accomplished in part through consolidating inefficient data centers and opening new ones. The cloud services has both internal and external components, where cloud services are used to deliver content for devices like the iPad, and internally, as a computing resource, where these cloud computing resources are provided internally as web services.  

There are nine primary data centers in the United States. Comcast is shifting more of them to its own control after years of relying on hosting services.

Comcast has also gotten into the data center market. The company now provides Ethernet capabilities that increase bandwidth, making data more accessible.

The Chief Infrastructure & Information Security Officer is responsible for directing all IT security projects and parameters across the company's various IT offices.

Other executives lead in infrastructure & systems services, data warehousing, BSS desktop solutions, wireless technology, end user support, and network engineering.

The Comcast Spotlight division’s technical staff is responsible for the backend systems that go into supporting the company’s advertising platforms.  The division has several teams, which either focus on the applications side or the systems in the data center. One side of the division engages in various application development initiatives, including those that involve the development of data systems for internal use, and to a lesser extent, for new client facing applications.  Another group is responsible for the division's proprietary hardware and software systems used in service delivery and the back office systems.  The Engineering group is concerned with technical operations and architecture for these infrastructure systems.  

Another side of the group provides technical support, which is handled by region, with managers in charge of supporting the division's staff in the West and the Midwest/North Central.  The division has invested heavily in data storage systems, nodes which handle Petabytes of data used in managing content.     

Sources at Comcast Corporation indicate the company's ESP, provisioning, and activation solutions causing the most strain on its network environment.

